comparisons.base_model_summary:
Binary search tree is a rooted, ordered binary tree data structure used for efficient searching, addition, and removal of data items. It has linear space complexity and can support constant-time insertions, deletions, and searches compared to unsorted arrays. Different variations exist to ensure worst-case performance, such as AVL trees. These trees have applications in sorting algorithms, set implementation, priority queues, and dynamic sets.

        This article provides a comprehensive overview of the binary search tree data structure, highlighting its advantages, limitations, and historical development. It covers its foundational elements like the concept, types, properties, space complexity, and various implementations along with their characteristics. By understanding this tree, one can effectively utilize it in computational problems ranging from data retrieval to sorting algorithms. Additionally, it explains how binary search trees can be adapted for more complex scenarios, such as implementing abstract data types and sorting algorithms, further enhancing their versatility and utility. </summary>

